question: What sets apart CS programs from SE programs?
walert_answer: There is no direct answer. It is easy between some programs, and not as easy between some programs. For example, within first and second year, it is easy to transfer between SE and CS programs. Also, if you go from SE or CS to IT, it is easy to transfer. However, going up, such as IT to CS, will require certain requirements and assessed on merit.
gold: The first two years of these two programs are near-identical. Then, in the third year of the SE degree, students spend a whole year (roughly 40 working weeks) in an industry placement. They work in a software firm engaging in all facets of software development process, from design to deployment. Final year (third in CS and fourth in SE) are slightly different, in that, SE students will do another large in-house project and more SE electives, while CS students will do a slightly smaller project and a few more core courses and electives.

question: Does Engineers Australia accredit RMIT's Software Engineering degree?
walert_answer: No. RMIT’s SE degree is very much software development focussed degree, and it does not teach principles of engineering design. Also, there is no advanced math courses, such as Calculus, engineering maths, and statistics in our SE degree. However, they still be required to one discrete maths subject. However, it meets the international standards in SE industry ACM and IEEE guidelines on SE curriculum, and also accredited by Australian Computer Society.

question: Does the school offer work placements?
walert_answer: Well, not directly. We do have a lot of industry contacts, as well as a full-time industry coordinator who will assist students to establish industry links. In addition, towards the second part of second year, we run a number of professional development activities to assist students to get themselves prepared for applying industry placements. In the worst comes to worst, we will transfer SE students to CS program if -- after every possible avenue is exhausted -- they cannot secure an industry placement.

question: What options are there for Work Integrated Learning experiences for RMIT CS students?
walert_answer: There is a multitude of WIL components available, some are part of the programs and mandatory and others are optional. SE students are required to do one-year industry placement and another 24CP project in their final year. Same for all three professional degrees. All other students are required by RMIT rules to do a capstone project in their final year. It involves with doing a project with an industry partner, or in some cases, an in-house project simulating a real industry scenario. In each case, they are assigned a project supervisor who work closely with you and industry partner to get student experience. In addition to these mandatory WIL requirements, every year we have summer projects and other industry events, such as ANZ hackathon, AIIA iAwards competition, and other coding/ security competitions.

question: Is it accurate to say that the IT industry in Australia has no future as every company outsources to India?
walert_answer: That’s a myth. Yes, some low-end jobs were outsourced such as call centres, however, there is a growing IT industry, especially, within startups, innovative IT technologies, such as home automation, Internet of things, machine learning, etc, which are not, and will not be, outsourced and Melbourne is always at the forefront of these developments. Also, IT-support jobs, in small to medium scale companies, will still remain locally. There were 91000 job adverts in the first half of 2021 alone. 530,000 (more than half a million, out of a workforce of 16.5 million) work in IT sector. What really matters is that job demand in IT sector is growing, for last 11 years (since 2007-08 downturn) and never looked back since 2007-08. Link: https://joboutlook.gov.au/Occupation.aspx?search=Career&code=2613 You can find the demand for other skills and compare it with ICT professionals and see it for yourself.

question: What are the disparities between the Bachelor of CS and Bachelor of CS (Professional) degrees?
walert_answer: The Professional version is just introduced, and first intake will be 2023. Students in the regular (3-yr version), if they perform really well in the first two years, they can apply for an internal transfer into the professional version (4-yr version). It is essentially added internship year to the regular program. The full-year internship (40 weeks) is similar to what Software Engineering students do in their third year. However, you may be able to choose a wider range of companies that suits your preferred career path (cyber security, data science, machine learning, etc).

question: How do CS and IT programs differ from each other?
walert_answer: CS program covers Computer Science core body of knowledge and will provide a solid foundation in the underlying concepts. It strikes a good balance between the theory and the application of these theories to the application of them into real-life scenarios (in application development). The IT program tip more into the applications with more emphasis on hands-on skills in various aspects of ICT (information and communication technology). Our IT degree has more degree of freedom (much more flexible) in customising the program to your taste, say, if you interested in explore in one aspect of IT (mobile app development, or networking, or security, or business analysis), you can choose your majors and minors in such a way, or if you prefer to go across the breadth.
